Yeah, there&#x27;s ways to screw up every method of coding, but I find favoring more and shorter functions tends to better outcomes.  Obviously you could reductio ad absurdum any code into something like:<p><pre><code>  function do_task() {
    do_step1();
    do_step2();
    do_step3();
  }

  function do_step {
    step1();
  }

  function do_step2 {
    step2();
  }

  function do_step3 {
    step3();
  }
</code></pre>
But I&#x27;ve rarely seen that be the problem.  It&#x27;s been far, far more common to see giant functions that are much more understandable when broken up.
